<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Forgiveness</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Thu May 6, 2010; substantive revision Fri Jan 16, 2026</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
To forgive is to respond in a particular way to someone who has
treated someone badly or wrongly. In paradigmatic cases, forgiveness
is a triadic relation between a wrong action &phi;, a wrongdoer and a
wronged victim; the victim forgives the wrongdoer for having done
&phi;. By forgiving, a victim can move on from &phi; while still
judging that it was a culpable wrong. It has been claimed that the
core of forgiveness is the giving up of certain negative emotions
towards the wrongdoer, or the forbearance of negative treatment of the
wrongdoer, or the restoration of the relationship with the wrongdoer,
or the alteration of the norms bearing on victim and wrongdoer. Much
philosophical discussion of forgiveness centers on three primary
questions: (1) What is the nature of forgiveness&mdash;what must one
do in order to forgive; (2) What is the scope of
forgiveness&mdash;when is one in a position to forgive and which
things can be forgiven; and (3) What are the norms governing
forgiveness&mdash;when is forgiveness morally good, right, or
praiseworthy?</p>
</div> 

